{
  "answer": "# Swaminarayan Knowledge Base \u2014 Panch Vartman (Five Moral Vows)\n\n---\ntitle: Panch Vartman \u2014 The Five Fundamental Vows of the Swaminarayan Sampradaya\nsource: Vachanamrut; Shikshapatri (Bhagwan Swaminarayan, 1826)\nurl: https://www.swaminarayan.org/panch-vartman\nverification_status: VERIFIED\ncategory: swaminarayan\n---\n\n## Content\n\nThe Panch Vartman (Five Vows / Five Codes of Conduct) are the foundational ethical commitments required of all initiated members of the Swaminarayan Sampradaya.\n\n**The Five Vows:**\n\n1. **Nishpapa (Ahimsa / Non-harm)**\n   Abstain from violence. Do not harm any living being unnecessarily. This prohibits meat eating for all initiates.\n\n2. **Nirmatsari (Non-intoxication)**\n   Complete abstinence from alcohol, drugs, tobacco, and intoxicating substances of all kinds.\n\n3. **Nischaurya (Non-theft)**\n   Do not steal or take anything that has not been given with consent. Act with complete honesty in all dealings.\n\n4. **Nishkam (Celibacy in mind and action)**\n   Maintaining purity of thought, word, and deed. For householders this means fidelity; for sadhus it means complete celibacy.\n\n5. **Nirlobha (Non-possessiveness / Non-greed)**\n   Detachment from material possessions, wealth, and status. Seeking only what is necessary and dedicating all resources to God's service.\n\n**Purpose:**\nThese five vows purify the individual's character and remove the obstacles to developing genuine devotion (bhakti) to Purushottam. They are prerequisites for deeper spiritual progress.\n\n**Initiation (Diksha):**\nWhen a devotee formally commits to the Panch Vartman at initiation, they receive kanthi (a tulsi wood beaded necklace) as a mark of initiation.\n\n**Universal Application:**\nUnlike caste-based Hindu ethical codes, the Panch Vartman applies equally to all members regardless of gender, caste, or social status \u2014 a socially revolutionary position for 19th century India.\n\nUniGuru Citation: Shikshapatri Verses 9-16; Vachanamrut Gadhada I-18; BAPS Swaminarayan Sanstha ethical framework",
